k]], 1982|ref=}}\n{{Mem/f|name=[[Kerry Mullis]]|chapter=[[Georgia Institute of Technology]], 1964|nota=Won the 1993 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for his development of the Polymerase chain reaction (PCR), a central technique in biochemistry and molecular biology which allows the amplification of specified DNA sequences}}\n{{Mem/f|name=[[Merrill Moore]]|chapter=[[Vanderbilt University]], 1924|nota=Psychiatrist and poet; neurologist at the [[Harvard Medical School]]|ref=<ref name=\"underwood41\">{{cite book|last1=Underwood|first1=Thomas A.|title=Allen Tate: Orphan of the South|date=2000|publisher=Princeton University Press|location=Princeton, New Jersey|isbn=9780691069500|oclc=44090472|page=41|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0M_iUdjxb3IC&pg=PA41&lpg=PA41&dq=Merrill+Moore+sigma+chi#v=onepage&q=Merrill%20Moore%20sigma%20chi|quote=Across the street, in the Sigma Chi fraternity, he found a distracted seventeen-year-old named Merrill Moore, who was well on the way to becoming the most prolific sonneteer in history.}}</ref>}}\n}}\n\n==Education==\n{{Mem/fstart|alist=\n{{Mem/f|name=[[William Andrew MacKay]]<sup>S</sup>|chapter=[[Dalhousie University]], 1950|nota=Former President of [[Dalhousie University]]|ref=}}\n{{Mem/f|name=[[Gregory H. Adamian]]<sup>S</sup>|chapter=[[Wesleyan]], 1948|nota=Former President and Chancellor of [[Bentley University]]|ref=}}\n{{Mem/f|name=[[David B. Ashley]]<sup>S</sup>|chapter=[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]], 1973|nota=President of the [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]]|ref=}}\n{{Mem/f|name=[[John Gabbert Bowman]]<sup>S</sup>|chapter=[[University of Iowa]], 1899|nota=[[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the [[University of Pittsburgh]] from 1921\u20131945. The [[Cathedral of Learning]], the second tallest educational building in the world, is dedicated to him.|ref=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sigmachi.org/1002158066-0|title=Membership Directory|publisher=[[Sigma Chi]]|accessdate=2016-04-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.or