he Chronicles of Narnia:<br> The Voyage of the Dawn Treader]]''\n|Michael Apted\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Tower Heist]]''\n|Brett Ratner\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[ReWined]]''\n|Ferdinando Vicentini Orgnani\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Hercules (2014 film)|Hercules]]''\n|Brett Ratner\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[I Saw the Light (film)|I Saw the Light]]''\n|Marc Abraham\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Freak Show (film)|Freak Show]]''\n|[[Trudie Styler]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2018\n|''[[Traffik (2018 film)|Traffik]]''\n|[[Deon Taylor]]\n|-\n|''[[Ant-Man and the Wasp]]''\n|[[Peyton Reed]]\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Black and Blue (2019 film)|Black and Blue]]''\n|rowspan=2|Deon Taylor\n| \n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Fatale (film)|Fatale]]''\n|\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''Beverly Hills Cop IV''\n| [[Adil El Arbi and Bilall Fallah]]\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0005883}}\n* [http://www.manhunter.net/gallery.html Quality screengrabs of Dante Spinotti's fine cinematography on ''Manhunter'' (1986)]\n* [http://movies2.nytimes.com/gst/movies/filmography.html?p_id=112345 Profile at ''New York Times'']\n* [http://www.theasc.com/magazine/jun98/lumin/pg6.htm Profile at American Cinematographer]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060520181403/http://www.cameraguild.com/interviews/chat_spinotti/spinotti_audio.htm Interview for International Cinematographers Guild]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051215100206/http://www.lighttools.com/spinotti.html Interview for LightTools]\n\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Cinematography 1985\u20132009}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spinotti, Dante}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Tolmezzo]]\n[[Category:Italian cinematographers]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:David di Donatello winners]]\n[[Category:American Society of Cinematographers members]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1943|8|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Tolmezzo]], [[Italy]]\n| occupation = Cinematographer\n| years_active = 1972-present\n}}\n'''Dante Spinotti''', [[A.S.C.]], A.I.C. (born August 22, 1943) is an [[Italy|Italian]] [[cinematographer]] and a member of the [[Board of Governors]] of the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]].<ref name=IMDb_Spinotti>{{cite web|title=Dante Spinotti|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0005883/|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref> He is known for his collaborations with directors [[Michael Mann]], [[Michael Apted]], and [[Brett Ratner]], and is frequently credited with helping to pioneer the use of high-definition [[digital video]] in [[cinematography]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://britishcinematographer.co.uk/dante-spinotti-special-feature/|title=Dante Spinotti - British Cinematographer|date=2015-05-09|work=British Cinematographer|access-date=2018-03-18|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/artisans/festivals/dante-spinotti-technology-new-workflow-directors-personalities-1201922150/|title=Dante Spinotti on Technology, New Workflow, Directors\u2019 Personalities|last=Caranicas|first=Peter|date=2016-11-18|work=Variety|access-date=2018-03-18|language=en-US}}</ref> He is a [[BAFTA Award for Best Cinematography|BAFTA Award]] recipient and two-time [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Academy Award]] nominee (for [[L.A. Confidential (film)|''L.A. Confidential'']] and [[The Insider (film)|''The Insider'']]).\n\n==Biography==\nSpinotti was born in [[Tolmezzo]], near the [[Austria]]n border. He began experimenting with still photography at the age of 11 with a camera given to him by his uncle, a [[cinematographer]] and [[Film director|director]] specializing in documentaries and newsreels. He worked as a [[camera operator]] on documentaries for much of his early career.\n\nAmong the more notable films he has worked on are ''[[The Last of the Mohicans (1992 film)|The Last of the Mohicans]]'', ''[[Heat (1995 film)|Heat]]'', and ''[[L.A. Confidential (film)|L.A. Confidential]]''. Spinotti also was the cinematographer for [[Brett Ratner]]'s films, such as ''[[Red Dragon (2002 film)|Red Dragon]]'' (2002), ''[[After the Sunset]]'' (2004), and ''[[X-Men: The Last Stand]]'' (2006).\n\nSpinotti has the distinction of being the cinematographer on both film versions of author [[Thomas Harris]]' ''[[Red Dragon (novel)|Red Dragon]]'': [[Michael Mann (director)|Michael Mann]]'s [[Manhunter (film)|1986 adaptation]] (titled ''Manhunter''), and [[Brett Ratner]]'s [[Red Dragon (2002 film)|2002 adaptation]] (which retains the novel's original title). He won the Golden Camera 300 award at the [[Manaki Brothers Film Festival]] in [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]] for lifetime achievement.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| {{dagger|alt=Films that have not yet been released}}\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Director\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1981\n|''[[La disubbidienza]]''\n|[[Aldo Lado]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=3|1983\n|''[[Cinderella '80]]''\n|Roberto Malenotti\n|\n|-\n|''[[Dream of a Summer Night]]''\n|[[Gabriele Salvatores]]\n|\n|-\n|''[[Hearts and Armour]]''\n|[[Giacomo Battiato]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1984\n|''[[Basileus Quartet]]''\n|[[Fabio Carpi]]\n|\n|-\n|''[[Cos\u00ec parl\u00f2 Bellavista]]''\n|[[Luciano De Crescenzo]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1985\n|''[[The Berlin Affair]]''\n|[[Liliana Cavani]]\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Dark Side of Love]]''\n|[[Salvatore Samperi]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1986\n|''[[Crimes of the Heart (film)|Crimes of the Heart]]''\n|[[Bruce Beresford]]\n|\n|-\n|''[[Manhunter (film)|Manhunter]]''\n|[[Michael Mann]]\n|\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[From the Hip (film)|From the Hip]]''\n|[[Bob Clark]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=4|1988\n|''[[Beaches (film)|Beaches]]''\n|[[Garry Marshall]]\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Legend of the Holy Drinker (film)|The Legend of the Holy Drinker]]''\n|[[Ermanno Olmi]]\n|\n|-\n|''[[Fair Game (1988 film)|Fair Game]]''\n|Mario Orfini\n|\n|-\n|''[[Illegally Yours]]''\n|[[Peter Bogdanovich]]\n|\n|-\n|1989\n|''[[Torrents of Spring (film)|Torrents of Spring]]''\n|[[Jerzy Skolimowski]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1990\n|''[[The Comfort of Strangers (film)|The Comfort of Strangers]]''\n|[[Paul Schrader]]\n|\n|-\n|''[[A Violent Life]]''\n|Giacomo Battiato\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=3|1991\n|''[[Frankie and Johnny (1991 film)|Frankie and Johnny]]''\n|Garry Marshall\n|\n|-\n|''[[Hudson Hawk]]''\n|[[Michael Lehmann]]\n|\n|-\n|''[[True Colors (1991 film)|True Colors]]''\n|[[Herbert Ross]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1992\n|''[[The Last of the Mohicans (1992 film)|The Last of the Mohicans]]''\n|Michael Mann\n|Nominated \u2013 [[American Society of Cinematographers Award for Outstanding Achievement in Cinematography in Theatrical Releases|American Society of Cinematographers Award for Outstanding Cinematography]]\n|-\n|''[[The End Is Known]]''\n|[[Cristina Comencini]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1993\n|''[[The Secret of the Old Woods]]''\n|Ermanno Olmi\n|\n|-\n|''[[Blink (film)|Blink]]''\n|rowspan=2|[[Michael Apted]]\n|\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Nell (film)|Nell]]''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1995\n|''[[Heat (1995 film)|Heat]]''\n|Michael Mann\n|Nominated \u2013 [[Chicago Film Critics Association Award for Best Cinematography]]\n|-\n|''[[The Quick and the Dead (1995 film)|The Quick and the Dead]]''\n|[[Sam Raimi]]\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[The Mirror Has Two Faces]]''\n|[[Barbra Streisand]]\n|\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[L.A. Confidential (film)|L.A. Confidential]]''\n|[[Curtis Hanson]]\n|[[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[BAFTA Award for Best Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[American Society of Cinematographers Award for Outstanding Achievement in Cinematography in Theatrical Releases|American Society of Cinematographers Award for Outstanding Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[