ry:Films set on islands]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:Sony Pictures Animation films]]\n[[Category:2009 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs\n| image          = Cloudy with a chance of meatballs theataposter.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Phil Lord<br />Christopher Miller]]\n| producer       = Pam Marsden\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* Phil Lord\n* Christopher Miller\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs]]''|[[Judi Barrett]] <br> [[Ron Barrett]]}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|<!--PER CAST BILLING BLOCK-->\n* [[Bill Hader]]\n* [[Anna Faris]]\n* [[James Caan]]\n* [[Andy Samberg]]\n* [[Bruce Campbell]]\n* [[Mr. T]]\n* [[Bobb'e J. Thompson]]\n* [[Benjamin Bratt]]\n* [[Neil Patrick Harris]]\n* [[Al Roker]]\n* [[Lauren Graham]]\n* [[Will Forte]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Mark Mothersbaugh]] <ref>{{cite web | url=https://variety.com/2009/digital/markets-festivals/cloudy-with-a-chance-of-meatballs-1200476076/ |title=Cloudy With a Chance of Meatballs |publisher=Variety|first=Peter |last=Debruge|date=September 17, 2009 |accessdate=September 23, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mutato.com/info/ |title=Info | publisher=Mutato Muzika |accessdate=September 23, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.wired.com/2009/08/geekdad-talks-cloudy-with-a-chance-of-meatballs-with-directors-chris-miller-phil-lord/ |title=GeekDad Talks Cloudy With a Chance of Meatballs with Directors Chris Miller & Phil Lord | publisher=Wired|date=August 6, 2009|accessdate=September 23, 2009}}</ref>\n| editing        = Robert Fisher Jr.\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Columbia Pictures]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Cloudy-with-a-Chance-of-Meatballs#tab=summary |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate=February 13, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Sony Pictures Animation]]<ref name=afi>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/64856?sid=38a42e29-5f9a-49d4-83fd-1e76dd5bd136&sr=4.117547&cp=1&pos=1|title=Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs  (2009)|work=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]]|accessdate=November 11, 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Sony Pictures Motion Picture Group#Sony Pictures Releasing|Sony Pictures Releasing]]<ref name=afi/>\n| released       = {{Film date|2009|9|12|Los Angeles|2009|9|18|United States|ref1=<ref name=\"HollywoodLAPremiere\" />}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes<ref name=afi/>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $100 million<ref name=\"BoxOfficeMojo\">{{cite web |title=Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs (2009) |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=cloudywithachanceofmeatballs.htm |work=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=December 20, 2010}}</ref>\n| gross          = $243 million<ref name=\"BoxOfficeMojo\" />\n}}\n\n'''''Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs''''' is a 2009 American [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] [[science fiction comedy]] film produced by [[Sony Pictures Animation]] and loosely based on the [[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs|1978 children's book of the same name]] by [[Judi Barrett|Judi]] and [[Ron Barrett]]. It was written and directed by [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller]] in their directorial debuts, and stars the voices of [[Bill Hader]], [[Anna Faris]], [[Bruce Campbell]], [[James Caan]], [[Bobb'e J. Thompson]], [[Andy Samberg]], [[Mr. T]], [[Benjamin Bratt]], [[Neil Patrick Harris]], [[Al Roker]], [[Lauren Graham]], and [[Will Forte]]. In the film, an aspiring inventor named Flint Lockwood develops a machine that can convert water into food following a series of failed experiments. After the machine gains sentience and begins to develop food storms, Flint must destroy the machine in order to save the world.\n\nThe film premiered in [[Los Angeles]] on September 12, 2009, and was released in the United States six days later on September 18 by [[Sony Pictures Motion Picture Group#Sony Pictures Releasing|Sony Pictures Releasing]] under its [[Columbia Pictures]] label. It earned over $243 million worldwide on a budget of $100 million,<ref name=\"BoxOfficeMojo\" /> and generally received critical praise toward its colorful visuals, humor, characterizations, and voice acting, while the simple character designs and plot were mostly criticized. The film has since been expanded into a [[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs (franchise)|franchise,]] with a sequel, ''[[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs 2]]'', released on September 27, 2013, as well as an [[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs (TV series)|animated television series based on the film]] premiering on [[Cartoon Network]] on February 20, 2017, with none of the original cast returning.\n\n== Plot ==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, plot summaries should be no more than 700 words. -->\nFlint Lockwood is a wannabe-scientist who lives in Swallow Falls, a fictional tiny island in the middle of the [[Atlantic Ocean]] that has [[sardines]] as the base of its economy, but the Baby Brent Sardines cannery shut down due to worldwide disgust of sardines as food, which was all the residents had to eat from then on. Flint lives with Tim, his widowed technophobic father, and his pet monkey, Steve. Despite Flint's enthusiasm, his inventions, including spray-on shoes, a flying car, a monkey thought translator, and rat birds, all end in failure.\n\nOne day, Flint invents a machine that transforms water into food called the \"Flint Lockwood Diatonic Super Mutating Dynamic Food Replicator\" (FLDSMDFR). Flint turns on the FLDSMDFR in his laboratory, but ends up overloading and subsequently shorting out the house's electrical supply. He then decides to power the machine by hooking it up to a nearby power plant. When he turns the machine back on, it ends up rocketing through town, destroying Sardine Land (a park conceived by the mayor) before ultimately shooting up into the sky. While recovering from his failure, Flint meets Samantha \"Sam\" Sparks, a weather intern whose big break was ruined by the incident. Their conversation is curtailed when bright clouds float over the town and begin to rain cheeseburgers.\n\nThe town rejoices in their renewed food choices, and Flint creates a communication device to send orders to the machine and order it to create different types of food. As a result, Swallow Falls (now renamed Chewandswallow) suddenly becomes a successful \"food tourism\" destination. Everything is going well until the townsfolk start greedily requesting food from Flint's machine. Flint notices that the food is beginning to grow larger in size. Although he is concerned that the food is starting to \"over mutate\", the now [[Obesity|morbidly obese]] mayor sees it as profitable for him and the city, and guilt trips Flint into continuing to make food rain.\n\nCitizens and worldly tourists in Chewandswallow are blissful until suddenly a large tornado formed of spaghetti and meatballs threatens the town. Flint rushes to his lab to turn off the FLDSMDFR by sending a \"kill code\" to stop the machine, but the mayor, while trying to stop him by throwing a giant radish at him, accidentally destroys the communication device after ordering a \"Vegas style [[Buffet#All-you-can-eat (AYCE)|all-you-can-eat buffet]]\". Now unable to control the machine, the FLDSMDFR creates a massive food storm which threatens the entire world. Flint gives up and loses hope; however, Tim encourages him to fix the mess. Flint gains self-confidence, places the kill code in a [[USB flash drive]], and builds a new flying car to reach and destroy the FLDSMDFR, with the aid of Sam, her cameraman Manny, Steve and Brent (namesake of the Baby Brent Sardines cannery).\n\nAs they approach the machine in the sky, they find that it is now serving as the core of a giant meatball which it created, where clouds go in the top and food comes out the bottom. The machine sends living food to attack them as the flash drive with the kill code flies out of the window.\n\nBack at Chewandswallow, the citizens and tourists escape while the last leftovers fall. Mt. Leftovers collapses, causing an avalanche of food that destroys the town. Despite the avalanche ravaging Flint's Lab, Tim manages to re-send the kill code to Flint's cell phone from there. Flint then goes inside the meatball, finds the machine, and connects the phone to a port. To his horror, Flint discovers that Tim accidentally sent him the wrong file, so he is unable to stop the FLDSMDFR. Instead, Flint uses his Spray-On Shoes formula on the machine, causing it to explode, seemingly killing him. With the machine destroyed, the food storm subsides and everyone is able to return safely to Chewandswallow. Flint is revealed to have survived the explosion and Tim finally shows his appreciation for his son and his inventions and Flint and Sam celebrate with a kiss. Meanwhile, the obese mayor is seen stranded in the middle of the sea, having eaten nearly all of his peanut butter and jelly sandwich boat, while sadly muttering to himself that his plan was not well thought out.\n\n==Voice cast==\n* [[Bill Hader]] as Flint Lockwood: a young, timid, unsuccessful but determined inventor and Sam's love interest.\n** Max Neuwirth as young Flint Lockwood.\n* [[Anna Faris]] as Sam Sparks: a formerly nerdy weather intern from [[New York City]] and Flint's love interest.\n* [[Neil Patrick Harris]] as Steve: Flint's sugar-addicted pet monkey who can communicate through a [[Speak & Spell (toy)|speak and spell]] thought-translating device.\n* [[James Caan (actor)|James Caan]] as Tim Lockwood: Flint's desperate but caring [[technophobia|technophobic]] [[fisherman]] father.\n* [[Bruce Campbell]] as Mayor Shelbourne: the corrupt, greedy and selfish mayor of Swallow Falls. Unhappy with his status as a small time mayor, he sees Flint as his route to greater success. He becomes obese through constant eating.\n* [[Andy Samberg]] as \"Baby\" Brent McHale: the arrogant and dim-witted mascot of Baby Brent's Sardines and Flint's former rival.\n* [[Mr. T]] as Officer Earl Devereaux: the town's athletic cop and Cal's father.\n* [[Bobb'e J. Thompson]] as Calvin 'Cal' Devereaux: Earl's young son.\n* [[Benjamin Bratt]] as Manny: Sam's [[Guatemala]]n [[cameraman]] and former [[Physician|doctor]], [[comedian]], and [[Aircraft pilot|pilot]].\n* [[Al Roker]] as Patrick Patrickson: the anchorman of the weather station.\n* [[Lauren Graham]] as Fran Lockwood: Flint's deceased mother who had always believed in her son and always expressed it unlike her husband Tim.\n* [[Will Forte]] as Joe Towne: a bearded [[redneck]] citizen of Swallow Falls who appears on numerous occasions throughout the film.\n* [[Angela V. Shelton|Angela Shelton]] as Regina Devereaux: Earl's wife and Cal's mother.\n\n==Production==\nOn May 9, 2003, a year after establishment, [[Sony Pictures Animation]] announced its first animated slate, including ''Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs'', a film adaptation of [[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs|the book of the same name]]. [[Paul and Ga\u00ebtan Brizzi|The Brizzi brothers]] were brought to direct the film, with Wayne Rice adapting the screenplay.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ball|first=Ryan|title=Sony Taps Six to Direct Animates Slate|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/features/sony-taps-six-to-direct-animated-slate/|accessdate=September 28, 2012|newspaper=Animation Magazine|date=May 9, 2003}}</ref> In 2006, it was reported that the film had been helmed by new directors and writers, [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Nguyen |first=Hanh |url=http://www.zap2it.com/movies/news/zap-sonycloudywithachanceofmeatballs,0,1483855.story |title=Sony Forecasts 'Chance of Meatballs' |work=Zap2it |date=August 16, 2006 |accessdate=July 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAfter a year working on the script, they were fired for story issues and replaced with new writers, who after a year were also fired. Lord and Miller were then re-hired in 2006. The two completely redid the script, this time with the creative input of their crew. The new draft had the protagonist as a failed inventor who wanted to prove himself to his town. The two were almost fired again after [[Amy Pascal]], then-head of [[Sony Pictures]], criticized the film for a lack of story. Although the film succeeded on the comedic front in the animatic stage, Pascal cited the lack of an anchoring relationship in the film as a failure in the story telling. Unable to create new characters and environments to suit the new story demands, the two elevated the character of the tackle shop extra to be the protagonist's father, thereby creating the relationship Pascal had requested. The pair's experience on ''Cloudy'' taught them two valuable lessons: the power of creative collaboration and the importance of emotion in a story.<ref>{{cite AV Media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LeP9fSlmgjc|title=Rewriting Collective Insights: Phil Lord at TEDxCoconutGrove |author= Phil Lord |publisher= TEDx Talks|date=October 11, 2012|accessdate=September 20, 2018 |via= [[YouTube]] }}</ref>\n\nOn September 18, 2008, [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] announced that [[Bill Hader]] and [[Anna Faris]] had signed on to voice the two lead characters, with [[James Caan]], [[Bruce Campbell]], [[Mr. T]], [[Andy Samberg]], [[Neil Patrick Harris]], [[Bobb'e J. Thompson]], [[Benjamin Bratt]], [[Al Roker]], [[Lauren Graham]], and [[Will Forte]] also in the voice cast.<ref>{{cite news |last=Siegel |first=Tatiana |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117992475.html |title=Hader, Faris spice up 'Meatballs |work=Variety |date=September 18, 2008 | accessdate=July 31, 2011}}</ref> Lord and Miller said later that year that it would be a homage to, and a parody of, disaster films such as ''[[Twister (1996 film)|Twister]]'', ''[[Armageddon (1998 film)|Armageddon]]'', ''[[The Core]]'', and ''[[The Day After Tomorrow]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sliceofscifi.com/2006/08/16/its-rainingfood |title=It's Raining.........Food? |accessdate=November 25, 2010 |last=Sloan |first=Sam |date=August 16, 2006 |work=Slice of SciFi}}</ref> ''Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs'' is the second film after ''[[Monster House (film)|Monster House]]'' that was made using the animation rendering software [[Arnold (software)|Arnold]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.movingpicturesmagazine.com/featuredarticles/specialfeature/cloudy-with-a-chance-of-meatballs |title=Sneak Peek: 'Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs' |accessdate=July 23, 2009 |last=Bharwani |first=Asim |date=July 2009 |work=MovingPicturesMagazine.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090730181209/http://www.movingpicturesmagazine.com/featuredarticles/specialfeature/cloudy-with-a-chance-of-meatballs |archive-date=2009-07-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs\n| type       = [[Soundtrack]]\n| artist     = [[Mark Mothersbaugh]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 15, 2009\n| recorded   = 2009\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Air Lyndhurst Studios]]<br />[[Angel Recording Studios|Angel Studios]]<br />[[Abbey Road Studios]]<br />[[Henry Wood Hall, London|Henry Wood Hall]]\n| genre      = [[Film score]]\n| length     = 65:16\n| label      = [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]]\n| producer   =\n| chronology = Mark Mothersbaugh\n| prev_title = [[Fanboys (film)|Fanboys]]\n| prev_year  = 2009\n| next_title = [[Ramona and Beezus]]\n| next_year  = 2010\n}}\n'''''Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs''''' is the [[soundtrack]] to the film of the same name, released under [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]] on September 15, 2009. The music of the film and this album are both credited to be composed and produced by American [[composer]] [[Mark Mothersbaugh]] of [[Devo]].\n\n===Track listing===\n{{Track listing\n| total_length      = 65:16\n| all_music         = [[Mark Mothersbaugh]], except where noted\n| extra_column      = Performer\n| title1            = Raining Sunshine\n| note1             = [[Matthew Gerrard]], Jay Landers, [[Charlie Midnight]]\n| extra1            = [[Miranda Cosgrove]]\n| length1           = 3:44\n| title2            = Swallow Falls\n| length2           = 0:47\n| title3            = Introducing Flint\n| length3           = 4:16\n| title4            = The Latest Invention\n| length4           = 1:23\n| title5            = The Mayor/Earl Warns Flint\n| length5           = 1:17\n| title6            = Sam's Big Break\n| length6           = 0:50\n| title7            = Powering Up\n| length7           = 1:05\n| title8            = Failure Again\n| length8           = 1:54\n| title9            = Meatier Shower\n| length9           = 3:10\n| title10           = A Father's Love\n| length10          = 1:19\n| title11           = Ice Cream Wonderland\n| length11          = 1:22\n| title12           = Snowball!\n| length12          = 1:15\n| title13           = The Mayor's Big Plan\n| length13          = 1:16\n| title14           = Activation and the Jell-O Dome\n| length14          = 1:39\n| title15           = Sam and Flint Bond\n| length15          = 2:00\n| title16           = Doubting Dad/Mutations\n| length16          = 2:57\n| title17           = The Spaghetti Twister\n| length17          = 3:08\n| title18           = Aftermath\n| length18          = 2:26\n| title19           = Flint's Determination\n| length19          = 2:44\n| title20           = The Food Storm\n| length20          = 2:08\n| title21           = The Mission Begins\n| length21          = 2:36\n| title22           = Outside the Meatball\n| length22          = 1:57\n| title23           = Inside the Meatball\n| length23          = 1:39\n| title24           = Earl Takes Charge\n| length24          = 2:00\n| title25           = Sentient Chickens\n| length25          = 2:42\n| title26           = Worldwide Chaos\n| length26          = 0:57\n| title27           = Anaphylactic Love\n| length27          = 1:41\n| title28           = Attack of the Gummi Bears\n| length28          = 1:40\n| title29           = Here's the Cheese\n| length29          = 1:25\n| title30           = The Heart of the Meatball\n| length30          = 1:17\n| title31           = Spray-On Triumph\n| length31          = 1:55\n| title32           = Flint Returns\n| length32          = 3:31\n| title33           = [[Sunshine, Lollipops and Rainbows]]\n| note33            = [[Marvin Hamlisch]], Howard Liebling\n| extra33           = [[Lesley Gore]]\n| length33          = 1:37\n|all_writing=}}\n\n== Release ==\n''Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs'' premiered on September 12, 2009, at the [[Fox Theater, Westwood Village|Mann Village Theatre]] in Los Angeles, California.<ref name=\"HollywoodLAPremiere\">{{cite web|title=L.A. Premiere of 'Cloudy With a Chance of Meatballs'/|url=http://www.hollywood.com/general/l-a-premiere-of-cloudy-with-a-chance-of-meatballs-59974162/|publisher=Hollywood.com|accessdate=January 14, 2017|date=September 12, 2009}}</ref> The film had its wide release on September 18, 2009, along with a digitally re-mastered release to [[IMAX 3D]] theatres.<ref>{{cite press release|author1=IMAX Corporation|title=Sony Pictures Animation's Cloudy With A Chance of Meatballs to be released in IMAX(R) 3D|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/sony-pictures-animations-cloudy-with-a-chance-of-meatballs-to-be-released-in-imaxr-3d-62266832.html|publisher=PR Newswire|accessdate=January 14, 2017|date=July 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Home media ===\nThe film was released on [[DVD]], [[Blu-ray]] Disc, and [[Universal Media Disc|PSP UMD]] on January 5, 2010 in the United States and Canada.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nemiroff |first=Perri |title=Cloudy With A Chance Of Meatballs Pours Onto DVD In January |url=http://www.cinemablend.com/dvdnews/Cloudy-With-A-Chance-Of-Meatballs-Pours-Onto-DVD-In-January-21356.html |accessdate=May 1, 2012 |newspaper=Cinema Blend |date=November 27, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=McCutcheon|first=David|title=Meatballs Cloud Up Home|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/11/09/meatballs-cloud-up-home|accessdate=October 17, 2012|newspaper=IGN|date=November 9, 2009}}</ref> A 3D Blu-ray was released on June 22, 2010. It was the first 3D Blu-ray sold individually in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |last=Calonge |first=Juan |title=Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs 3D Blu-ray Announced |url=http://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=4732 |accessdate=March 23, 2012 |newspaper=Blu-ray.com |date=June 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Art book ===\nIn August 2009, Insight Editions published a companion book to the film called ''The Art and Making of Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Silver |first=Curtis |title=Get Visual With the Art of Cloudy With a Chance of Meatballs |url=https://www.wired.com/geekdad/2009/10/get-visual-with-the-art-of-cloudy-with-a-chance-of-meatballs |accessdate=August 25, 2012 |newspaper=Wired |date=October 21, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Art and Making of Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs (Hardcover) |url=https://www.amazon.com/The-Making-Cloudy-Chance-Meatballs/dp/193378489X |work=Amazon.com |accessdate=August 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n=== Critical response ===\nReview aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 86% of critics gave positive reviews based on 142 reviews with an average rating of 7.3/10. The consensus statement reads, \"Quirky humor, plucky characters and solid slapstick make this family comedy a frenetically tasty time at the movies.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1196077-cloudy_with_a_chance_of_meatballs |title=Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs |publisher= [[Fandango Media]] |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] it has a weighted average score of 66 out of 100, based on 24 reviews, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/cloudywithachanceofmeatballs |title=Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs |work=Metacritic |publisher=CBS Interactive |accessdate= February 20, 2020 }}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A-\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kaufman|first1=Amy|title='Cloudy With a Chance of Meatballs 2' is No. 1 on crowded weekend|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-box-office-cloudy-meatballs-rush-20130929-story.html|accessdate=October 14, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=September 29, 2013|quote=Both installments received an average grade of A-, according to market research firm CinemaScore.}}</ref>\n\nErnest Hardy of ''[[LA Weekly]]'' stated the film \"is smart, insightful on a host of relationship dynamics, and filled with fast-paced action\". Hardy also applauded the 3-D effects which \"are wonderful, full of witty sight gags that play out both center-screen and on the periphery\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Hardy|first=Ernest|title=Movie Reviews: Cloudy With a Chance of Meatballs, Jennifer's Body, Love Happens |url=http://www.laweekly.com/2009-09-17/film-tv/movie-reviews-cloudy-with-a-chance-of-meatballs-jennifer-39-s-body-love-happens/ |accessdate=September 28, 2012|newspaper=LA Weekly |date=September 16, 2009}}</ref> [[Michael Phillips (critic)|Michael Phillips]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' gave the film a mixed review stating that \"Crazy doesn't always equal funny, and the gigantism of this 3-D offering's second half puts a damper on your enjoyment. But look: This film wasn't made for you, or me. It was made for dangerously, easily distracted 9-year-olds.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Phillips|first=Michael|title='Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs' -- 2 1/2 stars|url=http://featuresblogs.chicagotribune.com/talking_pictures/2009/09/cloudy-with-a-chance-of-meatballs-2-12-stars.html|accessdate=September 28, 2012|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=September 17, 2009}}</ref> [[Kyle Smith]] of the ''[[New York Post]]'' gave the film two stars stating that the animated film \"greatly expands on the kids' book on which it's based in a clever and engaging first half. But the second half leaves a foul aftertaste.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/forecast_fishy_7qJFRN3u9DV46qbUD57d0O |title=Forecast: Fishy |work=New York Post |accessdate=September 19, 2009 |first=Kyle |last=Smith |date=September 18, 2009}}</ref> Animator [[John Kricfalusi]], known for his generally negative opinions on modern animation, did a review of the film on his blog, saying that \"It was an optimistic portent of what ''could'' be. It's basically an undirected film\u2014but one that allowed many of the artists to take nothing scenes and add some kind of cleverness, design and action to the formulaic events being told by the story.\"<ref>{{cite web |url = http://johnkstuff.blogspot.com/2009/09/review-of-meatballs.html |title = John K Stuff: Review Of Meatballs |last = Kricfalusi |first = John |publisher = [[Blogspot]] |date = 21 September 2009 |website = John K Stuff |accessdate= 2 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\n=== Box office ===\n''Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs'' earned a total of $243 million on a reported budget of $100 million. Of the gross, 51%, or $124,870,275, came from the domestic market, while the rest, $118,135,851, from other territories.<ref name=\"BoxOfficeMojo\" /> For the film's marketing, Sony spent $43.3 million in the United States, and $26 million in other countries.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Litt|first1=Stefan|title=Smurfs 3|url=https://wikileaks.org/sony/emails/emailid/48419|publisher=WikiLeaks|accessdate=August 20, 2015|date=November 26, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150820171328/https://wikileaks.org/sony/emails/emailid/48419|archivedate=August 20, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The film earned $8,137,358 on its opening Friday, and ranked #1 at the box office with a total of $30.3 million for the first weekend.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gray |first=Brandon |title=Weekend Report: Moviegoers Feast on 'Meatballs,' Slim Pickings for 'Jennifer' |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2615&p=.htm |accessdate=September 28, 2012 |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date=September 21, 2009}}</ref> On its second weekend, it remained at #1 with a decrease of only 17%.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gray |first=Brandon |title=Weekend Report: Blue Skies for 'Cloudy,' Hazy Starts for 'Surrogates,' 'Fame' |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2616&p=.htm |accessdate=September 28, 2012 |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date=September 28, 2009}}</ref> It currently holds the record for third-largest opening weekend in the month of September.<ref name=\"BoxOfficeMojo\" />\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Group !! Category !! Recipient !! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[37th Annie Awards|Annie Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|title=37th Annual Annie Nominations and Awards Recipients |url=http://annieawards.org/legacy37th.html |work=AnnieAwards.org |accessdate=February 7, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100815022604/http://annieawards.org/legacy37th.html |archive-date=August 15, 2010 }}</ref>\n| Animated Effects\n| Tom Kluyskens\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[Annie Award for Best Animated Feature|Best Animated Feature]]\n!\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Directing in a Feature Production\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Writing in a Feature Production\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[15th Critics' Choice Awards|Broadcast Film Critics Association Awards]]<ref>{{cite news |title=15TH ANNUAL CRITICS CHOICE MOVIE AWARDS (2010) \u2013 BEST PICTURE: THE HURT LOCKER |url=http://www.criticschoice.com/movie-awards/15th-annual-critics-choice-movie-awards-2010-best-picture-the-hurt-locker |accessdate=February 7, 2012 |work=CriticsChoice.com |date=November 21, 2011}}</ref>\n| [[Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Animated Feature|Best Animated Feature]]\n!\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[67th Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Awards]]<ref>{{cite web |title=THE 67TH ANNUAL GOLDEN GLOBE AWARDS NOMINATIONS |url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/blog/2009/12/the-67th-annual-golden-globe-awardsnominations |work=GoldenGlobes.org |accessdate=February 7, 2012 |date=December 15, 2009 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120731165752/http://www.goldenglobes.org/blog/2009/12/the-67th-annual-golden-globe-awardsnominations |archive-date=2012-07-31 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Animated Feature Film|Best Animated Feature Film]]\n!\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[Satellite Awards 2009|Satellite Awards]]<ref>{{cite web |title=2009 Satellite Awards |url=http://www.pressacademy.com/award_cat/2009 |work=PressAcademy.com |accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref>\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Animated or Mixed Media Feature|Best Animated or Mixed Media Feature]]\n!\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Visual Effects Society Awards 2009|Visual Effects Society Awards]]<ref>{{cite web |title=8th Annual VES Awards |url=http://www.visualeffectssociety.com/ves-awards/previous/8th-annual |work=VisualEffectsSociety.com |accessdate=February 7, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130118060657/http://www.visualeffectssociety.com/ves-awards/previous/8th-annual |archive-date=January 18, 2013 }}</ref>\n| Outstanding Animation in an Animated Feature Motion Picture\n|Pete Nash, Chris Juen, Alan Hawkins, Mike Ford\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Effects Animation in an Animated Feature Motion Picture\n|Rob Bredow, Dan Kramer, Matt Hausman, Carl Hooper\n| {{Nom}}\n|}\n\n==Expanded franchise==\n{{main|Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs (franchise)}}\n\n===Sequel===\n{{main|Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs 2}}\nA sequel, titled ''[[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs 2]]'', was released on September 27, 2013. Directed by [[Cody Cameron]] and Kris Pearn, and it is based on an original idea, where Flint and his friends must again save the world from his food machine, which survived the explosion in the prequel. This time, the machine gains the ability to produce living food beasts.<ref name=\"PRNewswire\">{{cite news |title=Delicious Voice Cast Storms In To 'Cloudy 2: Revenge Of The Leftovers' |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/delicious-voice-cast-storms-in-to-cloudy-2-revenge-of-the-leftovers-166902936.html |accessdate=August 25, 2012 |newspaper=PR Newswire |date=August 21, 2012 |author=Sony Pictures Animation}}</ref> Most of the main cast reprised their roles, with [[Terry Crews]] replacing [[Mr. T]]. New cast also includes [[Kristen Schaal]] as orangutan Barb, and [[Will Forte]] in his new role of Chester V.<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite news |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |title=CAUTION: Food may eat YOU in 'Cloudy With a Chance of Meatballs' sequel -- EXCLUSIVE |url=http://family-room.ew.com/2012/08/21/cloudy-2-exclusive |accessdate=August 22, 2012 |newspaper=Entertainment Weekly |date=August 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Television series===\n{{main|Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs (TV series)}}\nOn October 9, 2014, [[DHX Media]] announced that it will develop and produce a television series based on the film franchise, titled ''Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs: The Series''.<ref name=DHXMTakingToTV /> The series will be traditionally animated and will consist of twenty-six 22-minute episodes.<ref name=DHXMTakingToTV /> It will take place before the first film, showing Flint Lockwood as a high school student who dreams of becoming a serious scientist.<ref name=DHXMTakingToTV /> In his adventures, he will be joined by Sam Sparks, a new girl in town and the school's \"wannabe\" reporter, along with Flint's dad Tim, Steve the Monkey, Manny as the head of the school's audiovisual club, Earl as a school gym teacher, Brent as a baby wear model, and mayor Shelbourne.<ref name=DHXMTakingToTV /> DHX Media will handle the global television and non-US home entertainment distribution, along with worldwide merchandising rights, while Sony will distribute home entertainment in the US.<ref name=DHXMTakingToTV>{{cite press release|title=DHX MEDIA AND SONY PICTURES ANIMATION TAKING CLOUDY WITH A CHANCE OF MEATBALLS TO TELEVISION|url=http://www.dhxmedia.com/press-room/590:dhx-media-and-sony-pictures-animation-taking-cloudy-with-a-chance-of-meatballs-to-television|publisher=DHX Media|accessdate=October 10, 2014|date=October 9, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010203905/http://www.dhxmedia.com/press-room/590%3Adhx-media-and-sony-pictures-animation-taking-cloudy-with-a-chance-of-meatballs-to-television|archive-date=2014-10-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> Commissioned by [[Teletoon]] in Canada, the series will air on [[Cartoon Network]] in the United States,<ref>{{cite press release|author1=Sony Pictures Animation|title=Sony Pictures Animation Announces 2017 & 2018 Slate|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/sony-pictures-animation-announces-2017--2018-slate-300287319.html|publisher=PR Newswire|accessdate=September 25, 2016|date=June 20, 2016}}</ref> and on the [[Boomerang (TV network)|Boomerang]] channel in other territories.<ref>{{cite press release|author1=DHX Media|title=DHX Media and Sony Pictures Animation's Cloudy With a Chance of Meatballs TV Series Goes Global|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/dhx-media-and-sony-pictures-animations-cloudy-with-a-chance-of-meatballs-tv-series-goes-global-530629831.html|publisher=PR Newswire|accessdate=October 9, 2015|date=October 5, 2015}}</ref> None of the original cast returned for the show and are replaced by Canadian voice actors.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs (video game)|''Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs'' (video game)]], based on the film.\n\n; Real life food spill disasters\n* [[Boston Molasses Disaster]]\n* [[Honolulu molasses spill]]\n* [[London Beer Flood]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n